{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Similar to the PV-to-SMILES generation, properties are predicted in an autoregressive manner: the model predicts the first property value using only the property [CLS] token ([CLS] P), then takes all previous outputs again to get the next prediction value, and so on (see Supplementary Fig. 1b).",
    "Although 53 properties that we've used can be calculated using the Python module, the purpose of this experiment is to verify that the data-driven way of property estimation coincides with the analytic approach.",
    "Specifically, we fed 1000 SMILES from the ZINC15 dataset 44, which are not contained in the pre-training dataset, to the pre-trained SPMM and generated their corresponding PV.",
    "Figure 4 is the scatter plot of the real property value against the generated output for 12 selected properties out of 53 that we used for pre-training.",
    "It is clear that SPMM's predicted property is very close to the actual value, and most of the data point lies on the y = x line."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Specifically, we fed 1000 SMILES from the ZINC15 dataset 44, which are not contained in the pre-training dataset, to the pre-trained SPMM and generated their corresponding PV."
  ]
